video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
Why does exercise multiply things, whether they are positive on their own, or negative on their own?  Here's my hypothesis:

Exercise increases blood flow throughout the body.  The heart beats faster, blood vessels dilate, the heat produced by metabolism elevates body temperature.  After exercise, the mitochondria are replenishing ATP stores, and calling for increased oxygen.  These are all reasons that exercise increases tissue perfusion both during and immediately after exercise.

Long-term, exercise promotes the growth of additional capillaries, leading to long-term increasee perfusion if tissues, especially skeletal muscles and cardiopulmonary tissues, but also liver and kidneys, and probably every tissue.

The result of the increased perfusion is that whatever you ingest, whether it is nutritious, poisonous, or nilpotent, reaches a greater fraction of the cells of your body.  The muscles in the back of your neck get more pickled from the alcohol you drank.  Your pancreas absorbs more of the CoQ10 that you took before your workout, etc.  

I think that simple mechanism is probably powerful enough to mask whatever more nuanced effects might be at play.

This is my opinion as someone who has exercised for long periods of time, and also who has not exercised at all for even longer periods of time.  When you are in the habit of exercising, your whole body feels more integrated.  When you are out of shape, you acquire more injuries that are localized.  E.g. my right knee is stiff when I wake up in the mornings, but my left knee is OK.  If I started an exercise routine, it would inherently correct that complaint (probably), but I would also stop having new complaints that are so isolated to one joint, one appendage, one organ.  I believe this because this is how it feels to me to be in my body.  Being in shape integrates wll the parts of the body simply by perfusing them all more thoroughly than being a lump does.
author: @HeathHunnicutt

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
I’d have to reread it but, from what I remember Dawkins talks about this in ‘The Selfish Gene’. I think Dr Von Hippel doesn’t make enough of a distinction between evolutionary motivated behaviors and socially motivated behaviors, especially when making a parallel between Hunter-Gatherers and Modern Humans.

Like, what are attractive qualities for a man? Depends entirely on the type of society that man lives in, when talking about Modern Man — what is socially acceptable, what is legal, what moral, what is desirable, etc. are all important variables that do not apply when referring to hunter-gatherers. Or at the very least, not in the same way Western society views these concepts today.

Our modern society has long plateaued as far as genetic mutations in the context of evolution and all it entails as a process. Modern humans have surpassed a lot of the biological imperatives that hunter-gatherers could not, because the type of society they operated in and what that meant for gene propagation. Even they consciously could have, they would have gone extinct.

We have the luxury of being able to override our evolutionarily ‘driven’ genes. 

What I mean to say with all my (probably) nonsense is that this whole idea of ‘risk taker’, ‘high testosterone’ and ‘nice guy’ is both reductive of our ability as a species to think for ourselves - and not our genitals - but also bypasses the simple concepts that sway us in most of our decision making, such as personal taste or preferred esthetics.

Dr Von Hippel, goes back and forth between ‘evolutionary qualities’ and modern preferences. He’s asked about evolutionary ideals and he talks about hips to waist ratio on Playboy Bunnies, then turns around and says that masculinity is directly correlated to testosterone. At times, he’s worryingly close to sounding like Red Pill Bro with a degree. Those are dangerous idea to be spreading under the guise of science, especially when it’s unclear whether he’s talking about a primeval gene propagating imperative or modern society’s genetic ideals. He’s giving simplistic notions on gender and sex a place that it should not have in a science based society, in 2025.
author: @educationaltoe

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
A couple of theories he has don't quite make sense to me - his data is interesting but I'm not convinced by his reasoning in many areas.

1) I DON'T believe robot nannies would reduce the incidence of parents abusing their kids. They may neglect them less but in terms of physical and sexual abuse - those things don't happen because parenting is hard work  - they happen because some parents are spiteful, selfish people who take out their frustrations with their status in life on their kids. The additional disconnect from other people that might come from parenting groups / family they interact with for babysitting etc would give them more autonomous time to stew / ruminate and become angrier. Most kids are abused by their primary care givers or the intimate partner of their primary care givers unfortunately. Abusive parents should get away with it less / for less time if the child has a broader network / community they can trust that actually cares. People who can rely on robots can isolate their kids which encourages MORE abuse. I hope we NEVER have robot nannies!

2) If homosexuality is a complex genetic trait - and we know that it exists on a spectrum in both men and women it's not about men being cleaner if they have homosexual genes. I would say men who are less dependant on women for sexual gratification and less needy for it + less able to get some sensual fulfillment (even if it's NOT actually sex) from contact with other people are less likely to become so frustrated / territorial with the women close to them that they murder them. Also less likely to be similarly sexually aggressive to female offspring and therefore their female offspring are not going to risk leaving their community for a smaller one with less chance for survival. Hence their genes are more likely to be passed on to a larger number of grandkids etc. His theory doesn't explain homosexuality in women. A woman who is less sexually jealous of her man is less likely to be nasty to other women he's been with or children he has by other women - makes for a more cohesive tribal environment where everyone is helping everyone to survive.

3) He says people who have happy marriages are just happy people before marriage and therefore stay married even if it's no better. However, by his own reasoning if being happy makes them more willing to make things work and try to work things out then it's the combination of two of these personality types that DOES make the relationship BETTER. The marriage IS better because they're not moping or fighting all the time. Maybe they don't earn more money etc. It's still BETTER.

comment_text:
Regarding the first part, where it says that wealthier people and city dwellers tend to be less happy than those who live in the countryside because they lack a support network or see their neighbors less... Personally, I don’t feel happy being surrounded by people I have nothing in common with, especially if I find them unintelligent.  

I was born and raised in a provincial town in Italy during the '90s and 2000s, and I always felt out of place. As a child, it was fine, but as I grew up, I started to feel surrounded by people who didn’t understand me, sometimes even by people I found quite stupid with narrow minds.  

Now, I have a few close friends, and while I know some of my neighbors and enjoy casual conversations with them, these relationships never turn into true friendships (also because some of them are 20-30 years older than me). Would I really be happier if I lived in the countryside and had more superficial relationships like this? I don’t think so.  

I believe that no matter where we live, there are only a few people who truly resonate with us, and that unhappiness often comes from internal struggles rather than external circumstances. I feel content with my small circle of friends and spending time at home with my hobbies.

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text: The ideas of what women find most attractive as seen through a patriarchal lens. It’s the constraints of patriarchy that drive women to seek security through someone like Bill Gates; not necessarily biological attraction. In fact, it’s been proven that most women will seek a high testosterone man to mate with around ovulation; not a rich old guy or nerd. Given testosterone decreases in a man’s thirties, this means that women, too, are most biologically attracted to a younger man. The truth is, by and large, men have been afforded the luxury of acting upon biological urges while women have had to suppress them out of fear. Now that women are freeing themselves from the constraints of patriarchy, they, too, will be afforded that luxury, and we’ll soon see a very different picture. In the meantime, if one were to simply study matriarchal societies where women are born with the ongoing support and security of their families throughout their lives, who a woman is attracted to will not likely include an old man with money. (Btw, it’s much, much harder for a man to have children, especially healthy children, as he ages, too. Maybe not as difficult as it is for a woman,  but he’s certainly not at his peak, and therefore, not a fertile woman’s first choice.) I look forward to seeing these viewpoints evolve as more women enter this sphere of study.

comment_text:
I must say. Out of all theses episodes I’ve watched, this is the one I found to be more of an opinion instead of fact. This doctor is spreading false information based on his opinion and not facts. There’s been a wide steady to see if people possess a gay gene and there has not been any solid determination that there is. And this doctor BILL is making claims that there are gay genes.

Dr. Bill Von Hippel’s claim that “there’s a gay gene” and that its expression determines whether someone is homosexual, heterosexual, or metrosexual is a BOLD statement, but it is not widely supported by genetic research.

What Does the Science Say?
	1.	No Single “Gay Gene” Exists – Large-scale genetic studies, such as the 2019 genome-wide association study (GWAS) published in Science, analyzed data from nearly half a million people and found that no single gene determines sexual orientation. Instead, they identified multiple genetic markers that may contribute in small ways.
	2.	Genetics Is Only One Factor – Sexual orientation appears to be influenced by a complex mix of genetic, hormonal, environmental, and social factors. While genetics may contribute, it does not function as a strict determinant.
	3.	No Evidence of a “Gay Gene in Everyone” – There is no mainstream genetic research supporting the idea that everyone has a universal “gay gene” that simply varies in expression. The GWAS study did find some genetic variants associated with same-sex attraction, but they were not universal, and their effects were small.

Evaluating the Claim

If Dr. Von Hippel’s statement were true, we would expect to see strong genetic correlations in twin studies, where identical twins (who share the same DNA) would always share the same orientation. However, studies show that while identical twins are more likely to have the same orientation than non-identical twins, they do not always match, suggesting non-genetic influences play a role.

Conclusion

While genetics plays a role in sexual orientation, the claim that everyone has a “gay gene” that determines different levels of sexuality does not align with current scientific evidence.

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
I have 3 thoughts:
1.) To me it's obvious that people in rural areas are more "happy" than urban dwellers & I think a huge factor that was not spoken about in this conversation is that in rural areas, humans live much closer to nature, to their natural rhythms, to the land & have access to forests, fields, the full expanse of the sky every day, etc. Not to mention a quiet, peaceful environment. This alone causes us to sleep better and generally enhances health, which directly influences how we "feel" each day. In a city (and I've lived in DC and NY for multiple years) - there is never quiet, there is high stimulation and very low access to the natural world, and what there is is often an afterthought, and still not the same peace, quiet and truly wild energy of rural areas. Being close to the natural world enhances happiness. 

2.) There are also a lot of us (neurodivergent - I'm an HSP) who actually find community quite grating and exhausting to navigate. I have lived in various intentional-community like settings and ended up super burnt out by them. We had meals together, recreation & working together, etc with very little time to be autonomous. I felt like I lost my essence and at the same time utterly burntout by the constant stimulation & people-ing. Then a few years after working as a teacher and normal 9-5 jobs in non profits (with decent community-like staff), left those. I have never been happier or more at peace living on my own and working from home. I found my boyfriend of 2+ years at a group salsa class (which is great for introverts b/c you rarely have to talk, you just learn the dance steps together) and I need him and my 2 close girlfriends. I have never been someone who needs large friend groups - in fact, that would exhaust me. I am plenty happy with my small circle, the natural world, pets and silence. I think I am not alone in this! Like, yes to fostering enriching relationships in this every independent world, but I also think it has to be done according to one's temperament & nervous system bandwidth. 

3.) I'd love to see an interview with someone (or various) who are child free by choice, not because it's too expensive or they cannot conceive, etc. I enjoy the guests who speak to sex/relationships/hormones, etc. always, but it does often seem like "having kids" is the positive thing and expected of everyone, and if you can't or don't want kids, that is the lesser choice. When in fact many of us who are plenty fertile and would actually do a good job at maternal/paternal roles just don't have that desire and never have. And we consider our calling in this lifetime to be divergent from that norm, although I think it's becoming more common. People don't just opt out of having kids b/c it's expensive or the world "is dangerous" - many of us simply have zero desire to be a parent, it seems utterly exhausting and would take away from the lifestyle we prefer and the work we feel called to do in the world.
author: @kellysuefitz

comment_text:
**Key Insights from "Behavioural Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr. Bill Von Hippel"**

Dr. Bill Von Hippel, a distinguished evolutionary psychologist, offers a captivating exploration of how our ancestral instincts influence modern human behavior, happiness, and societal trends. In a wide-ranging conversation, he examines topics from declining fertility rates to the effects of technology on relationships, weaving together evolutionary psychology with practical insights for navigating contemporary life. Below are the key insights distilled from this discussion, culminating in a conclusion that ties these threads together.

------

1. **Declining Fertility Rates and the Rise of Individualism**

- **Insight:** Fertility rates are dropping worldwide, with many industrialized nations seeing reproductive rates below the 2.1 children per woman needed to sustain populations. By 2100, some countries may halve in size. Marriage rates are also declining, and solo living has surged—1 in 7 Americans now live alone, up from 1 in 100 in 1850.
- **Significance:** These shifts signal a move toward individualism, where personal autonomy often trumps communal bonds. Von Hippel suggests that modern life's challenges—like the perceived difficulty of raising children—discourage reproduction, despite our evolutionary drive for sex rather than a direct desire for offspring. This disconnect, amplified by birth control, separates sexual activity from its reproductive outcomes.

------

2. **The Happiness Paradox: Wealth vs. Well-Being**

- **Insight:** Despite significant gains in wealth and living standards since the 1940s, happiness levels in the U.S. and similar nations remain flat. Rural dwellers, though less affluent (25% poorer than urbanites), report higher happiness due to stronger social ties, while city life fosters isolation amid crowds.
- **Significance:** Von Hippel highlights a paradox: material progress doesn’t guarantee emotional fulfillment. Urban environments prioritize autonomy—freedom to pursue individual goals—but this often erodes the social connections essential for happiness. The Hadza tribe, a hunter-gatherer group in Tanzania with over 90% reporting happiness, exemplifies how interdependence outweighs autonomy in fostering well-being.

------

3. **Evolutionary Attraction: Honest Signals of Quality**

- **Insight:** Attraction stems from evolutionary cues of fitness. For men, traits like risk-taking, humor, and ambition signal genetic quality and capability—hard-to-fake "honest signals." For women, physical markers like the hip-to-waist ratio correlate with fertility, with fat distribution (e.g., on thighs and buttocks) aiding fetal brain development.
- **Significance:** These instincts persist in modern dating. Men’s risk-taking (linked to high testosterone) attracts partners, though it subsides post-pairing to prioritize family stability. Women’s fertility signals remain consistent across cultures, explaining why certain body shapes endure as attractiveness standards, even as social preferences evolve.

------

4. **Technology’s Double-Edged Sword**

- **Insight:** Dating apps and pornography reshape social and sexual dynamics. Tinder amplifies competition (20% of men get 80% of swipes), while pornography—a recent phenomenon—offers a surrogate for real intimacy, reducing sexual activity among young people (down from 80% to 60-70% between 2006 and 2012 among 18-25-year-olds).
- **Significance:** Technology exploits evolutionary reward systems but often leaves us unfulfilled. Dating apps favor superficial traits, sidelining deeper qualities like kindness, while pornography’s accessibility (tripled in consumption over the same period) may deter real-world connection, contributing to isolation and declining fertility.

------

5. Neurodivergence as an Evolutionary Asset

- **Insight:** Conditions like ADHD and autism may have fueled human innovation. In ancestral settings, neurodivergent traits—unconstrained by social norms—likely drove inventions, with ADHD’s high energy suiting dynamic hunter-gatherer tasks rather than modern monotony.
- **Significance:** Today’s structured environments amplify these conditions’ challenges, yet their historical value suggests a need for adaptive settings that harness diverse thinking. Von Hippel posits that neurodivergence, possibly exacerbated by modern toxins, remains a key to creativity and progress.

------

6. **Religion, Meaning, and Happiness**

- **Insight:** Religious participation boosts happiness, doubling it among regular attendees, not due to doctrine but through community and purpose. Even non-religious prayer enhances well-being, reflecting a universal need for meaning—what Von Hippel calls a "god-shaped hole."
- **Significance:** Humans crave purpose, and religion fulfills this by fostering connection and structure. Wealthy individuals, often socially isolated, gain more from religious socializing than poorer, interdependent communities, underscoring the link between meaning, connection, and mental health.

------

7. **Power and Social Dynamics**

- **Insight:** Human power derives from capabilities and networks, not just physical might. Displays vary culturally—individualistic societies flaunt wealth (e.g., America), while collectivist ones value modesty. True power requires toughness and kindness to build supportive alliances.
- **Significance:** Unlike other species, humans leverage cooperation for dominance, a trait honed over millions of years. Understanding these dynamics—balancing strength with empathy—offers a blueprint for influence in personal and professional spheres.

------

8. **Practical Pathways to Happiness**

- **Insight:** Happiness hinges on prioritizing family, shared experiences, and "idle" social time over material wealth. Von Hippel advocates balancing autonomy with connection—e.g., eating together to share stories, a nod to ancestral bonding rituals.
- **Significance:** These actionable steps counter modern isolation. Spending on experiences (not possessions) and fostering interdependence align with our evolutionary needs, offering a roadmap to fulfillment amid autonomy’s allure.

------

**Conclusion**

Dr. Von Hippel’s insights reveal a central tension: our evolutionary past equips us for connection, yet modern life pushes us toward autonomy, often to our detriment. Declining fertility, stagnant happiness despite wealth, and technology’s mixed blessings all stem from this imbalance. By understanding attraction’s roots, neurodivergence’s gifts, and the power of meaning and networks, we can reclaim what we’re wired for—community and purpose. His practical advice—prioritize family, embrace experiences, and reconnect—bridges our ancestral instincts with today’s challenges, urging us to reflect and realign for a happier, more connected future.

comment_text:
I think people put too much emphasis on being "happy" and seeking "happiness."
Happiness is one emotion in a broad range of emotions that humans experience daily.  Trying to stay in a state of happiness is like trying to keep an ice-cream cone from melting on a hot day.  Just eat the icecream when you get it.. savor every bite in the moment, and then recall the memory of the experience often in your mind, recreating the feelings you had days/years after the event. 
If there's one thing people should seek is inner peace. It's when you connect with the true, eternal self that exists under the emotions and ups and downs of human life. It's the self that's there when the mind is not thinking thoughts. It's the self that's there when you release identification with your mind and body. It's the real you, eternal, whole, complete and perfect, regardless of age, circumstance and status. If you can connect with that inner peace, which is your true self, your true nature, then you ride the roller coaster of life and don't cling to any positive emotions or fear any negative ones. Inner peace is what we should be working on discovering and maintaining as human beings, not happiness.

comment_text:
ACTUALLY…. Men’s fertility does decline with age

Though not as sharply as women’s. While men continue to produce sperm throughout their lives, several factors contribute to reduced fertility as they get older:
	1.	Decline in Sperm Quality – Sperm count, motility (movement), and morphology (shape) tend to decrease with age, making conception more difficult.
	2.	Increased DNA Damage – Older men’s sperm have a higher risk of DNA fragmentation, which can lead to a higher chance of miscarriage or genetic conditions in offspring.
	3.	Lower Testosterone Levels – Testosterone, which plays a role in sperm production, tends to decline with age, potentially reducing fertility.
	4.	Longer Time to Conception – Studies show that it often takes longer for couples to conceive when the male partner is older, even if the female partner is young.
	5.	Higher Risk of Genetic Conditions – Advanced paternal age (usually 40+) is linked to a higher risk of conditions like autism, schizophrenia, and certain genetic mutations in offspring.

While men don’t experience menopause like women, fertility gradually declines, and the risks associated with fathering children increase with age.

I think a really important factor in why we don't spend time with our neighbours, is that our time seems so precious and we already sacrifice so much of our day doing work related things. And coming home and complaining to your neighbour (which inevitably you will)  doesn't feel like the first option in a society that is now accepting burn out and personal space. 

Space allows for personal development to become a better person and take on less habits of our neighbours that we don't like. Moderation within moderation I suppose. Yes we should spend more time in communities. Lots of us don't have neighbours who want to be social back or make the social game easy. As a neurodiverse person it's already really hard to find acceptance within society unless you're doing the system that everyone else does. For example I don't drink anymore, which completely segregates most of my UK community, because lots of people simply haven't caught up to the modern way or understand what that means. It's a fragmented societal problem I'm seeing so much of. 

No shade to Dr Hippel, I think what he's saying is truly fantastic, I just wish that the world would crank up less demand and/or hustle culture to pave the way for allowing those energy levels to exist, and not to the point of social burn out and expectation. The course proved many simple facts: human beings need evidences/confirmation to be happy, and our happiness often depends on external and internal factors. In fact, each of us today has more than ancient royalty ever did , with modern conveniences, access to information, better education, healthcare, and overall stability. So I have three old vehicles instead of one new one, and whenever I switch vehicles, they seem sort of 'new' to me again, and I get to enjoy something different about them as opposed to what I drove for the past week or so. I used to have a motorcycle, too, and when I was young, I drove it every day to save money on gas. Doing that, made it seem like nothing special, even though it was a top end high performance motorcycle. But it became 'just transportation' because it was all I used. Just as if you own a Ferrari, if you use it all the time, it becomes 'the car'. JUST the car. Because you have it all the time, you don't appreciate all the great things about it, because it becomes nothing special. 
Hope this concept helps someone. Keep some things as once in a while luxuries. STuff that you don't have all the time. Then you will enjoy them more.

It is not the "only" way, of course. But if you take it away, the result may be adults with even less resilience, self-discipline, etc.

To be fair to the guest, if he has a newborn at home - he wouldn't be the first person to wish for some "magical someone" to help out, LOL.  However, even this feeling/need pushes parents to "get out" and meet other parents to share some of the load (meet for playgroups, watch each other's children, etc.)

My hope is that we can create intentional childcare/school/neighborhood community centers to recreate the multi-generational extended family structures of the past (a place where both adults and children can get their developmental needs met while sharing and working alongside others). Gardens, canning/other food storage, classes in various skills (bread making, personal finance, DYI home repairs/building, auto maintenance, sewing/knitting, etc.), as well as potluck dinners, music/poetry readings, and so on, could take place there (as the community wants them).

I think this would work better than robots for addressing the isolation and lack of social interactions that your guest properly identified.

I've often pointed out that we created spaces like gyms to offset the effects of our modern sedentary lifestyles. However, we have failed to create and provide environments that replace essential experiences needed for healthy human development.  I believe, if we do this, we can fix many (if not most) of the problems that we are currently facing.

comment_text:
@@lyongarith  When I said "not discussed," I meant on podcasts like this one (Jocko Willis, Chris Williams, Rich Roll, Tom Bilyeau, etc.).  I may be wrong, but I will guess that (without Googling it) you may not know much about Montessori theory.  And that would be BECAUSE WE DON'T TALK ABOUT the various SCHOOLS OF THOUGHT relating to the first years of life and childhood in general.  Do we talk about Dynamic Systems Theory?  the Developmental Origins of  Health and Disease?  Sensitive Periods of Brain Development?   (The brain is 85% adult size by age 3 and 90% volume by age 5 or 6. )

I said this in an earlier post, but I will say it again.  We have created GYMS and WORKOUT routines because we have acknowledged that modern sedentary life does not provide needed environment/movement opportunities for healthy adults.  WHAT WE ARE FAILING TO SEE is the way that modern life IS IN DIRECT CONFLICT WITH healthy human development (aka childhood).  In the book ENDANGERED MINDS - WHY OUR CHILDREN DON'T THINK  (1990),  Dr. Jane Healy said that the brains of children today resemble those of patients with traumatic brain injuries...except rather than loosing functions...they are never being developed in the first place.  (And things have gotten worse, not better, since 1990 - and now those kids are having kids.)  If you want to know THE CAUSE of so many of the social problems we are facing - it is that we are no longer meeting the biological needs of human development.  

We simply cannot thrive in any domain (physical, cognitive, social/emotional, communication, adaptive/resilient) if basic biological requirements are absent.   This is not a political topic.  It is a physiological reality. This isn't about telling people how to raise their children.  It's about information and awareness. Early childhood experiences impact long-term physycial and mental health as well as human capital, productivity,  social skills, contributions to teams/community and so on.   

There is actually NO TOPIC MORE IMPORTANT.   Adults must intentionally PROVIDE essential environments to protect human flourishing during formative years  

SO, AM I CALLING OUT MEN?  YES, I am.   Men need to step up and get their heads in the game.  Discussions about human development should not only take place if they include power tools and robots.  (LOL)

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
It’s an average. You add up all the data points (in this case the number of children had by each woman in the sample) then divide by the number of data points (the number of women who’s children you were counting). If you had 3 women in your sample, woman A with 3 children, woman B with 1 child and woman C with no children, the total number of children in the sample is 3 + 1 + 0 = 4
Divide by the number of women in the sample and you get 4/3 or 1.333333
The fertility rate for that sample is 1.3333333 children per woman.
author: @bananewane1402

video_title: The Sex Psychologist: We're Not Having Enough Sex! Fat Makes You Attractive! Dr Bill Von Hippel
comment_text:
⁠@@maxwillsonIf a sample of 2 women had one child each, the average would be (1 + 1)/2 = 1 child per woman.

If a sample of 2 women only had one child between them (they’re a lesbian couple now), the average would be 1/2 = 0.5 children per woman.

comment_text: Secularization is a main driver of low birth rates.  Religions restrict sexual behavior in some ways, which encourages marriages of some kind, and usually religions encourage people to raise children to follow their faith.  I wonder if having school choice that includes religious schools, including for vocational and university education, would raise the birth rate.  Having school choice across the educational spectrum might result in quality non-profit vocational schools that cater to men.  If you put the vocational program on the college campus (small, Christian liberal arts college, mostly women), and have both groups participate in chapel and mandatory service project trips, then people would meet marriage minded people.  Unfortunately, even though most private non-profit schools at all levels spend less per pupil than state schools, students pay much more to go to the small private liberal art colleges.  These families and students end up going into debt to pay for the education, even though the state school charges less.  This disparity in funding probably affects ultimate family size.  If these students received the exact same subsidy as the public university student, they would have less debt, and since these people generally want to marry and have three or four children (if they can afford it).  In 19th century America, most schools had some element of religion, most charitable activities were religious and so were many societies for young people, such as the Chataquaua movement.  Most people lived in small towns with lots of church participation, but most people were very poor.  Nevertheless, the religious values helped prevent out of wedlock births and the temperance movement helped curb some of the out of control drinking.  We can learn a lot from studying the values and habits of the small farmers, small businessmen and skilled workers.  Many of practices and values they had  have been lost in secular education and urbanization, to everyone's long term detriment.

@  Who is this “We” youre referring to? Men who might want to have children some day.  It’s not all men and it’s certainly not something that should be stated in a podcast like this as it is not factual and it is extremely sexist. Saying that a woman’s attractiveness is based on her fertility is a reductive and outdated view that can come across as misogynistic, even if it’s rooted in evolutionary psychology. While biological factors may play a role in what people find attractive, reducing a woman’s value to her reproductive capability ignores her individuality, personality, intelligence, and agency.

People are not just biological beings but also social and emotional ones. In modern society, attraction is shaped by a wide range of factors, including personal compatibility, emotional connection, shared interests, and mutual respect. Stating that fertility is what makes a woman attractive not only dismisses women who are infertile or past childbearing age but also reinforces a narrow and limiting view of female worth.

Should people say it? Well, they can, but they should also expect pushback. It’s not inherently wrong to discuss biological influences on attraction, but when phrased in an absolute way, it dehumanizes women and reduces them to their biological functions rather than seeing them as whole people.

comment_text:
Ever heard of the Grandmother Hypothesis? It challenges the idea that women lose value or attractiveness once they are no longer fertile. It suggests that postmenopausal women have played a crucial evolutionary role, not just in their families but in society as a whole.

Here’s how it counters the fertility-based argument:
	1.	Survival Advantage – Unlike most mammals, human women live long past their reproductive years because their wisdom and experience provide benefits to the community. Evolution would not favor longevity if a woman’s value were only tied to fertility.
	2.	Wisdom and Influence – Older women hold valuable knowledge, from survival strategies to social dynamics. In many cultures, they are respected as leaders, healers, and advisors. This shows that a woman’s worth extends far beyond youth and fertility, rooted in her accumulated insight and ability to guide others.
	3.	Long-Term Bonds vs. Short-Term Attraction – If human attraction were purely about fertility, emotional intelligence and long-term bonds wouldn’t matter so much. Men across cultures appreciate wisdom, humor, and companionship—qualities that only deepen with age.

So, the idea that a woman is only attractive when fertile is outdated. Women’s evolutionary significance and attractiveness are rooted in their wisdom, making them essential at every stage of life.
